ternal cash source for supporting broader platform investment.** It is the only segment generating a positive surplus of Adjusted EBITDA over its own capital needs, producing $2,990M in excess cash-proxy in FY2025. Key strengths include:\n\n- **62.9% Adjusted EBITDA margin** on $11,387M in revenue, demonstrating exceptional operating leverage from the Starlink satellite constellation.\n- **86.2% year-over-year Adj. EBITDA growth**, outpacing revenue growth (49.8%) as the segment scales.\n- **99.9% subscriber growth** in FY2025, indicating the business is still in a high-growth phase.\n- A relatively capital-light marginal growth model: each incremental subscriber requires minimal additional satellite infrastructure once the constellation is deployed.\n\nNo other segment comes close. The Space segment generated only $653M in Adj. EBITDA against $3,832M in capex, and the AI segment is deeply negative on both metrics.\n\n### Risks If Connectivity Growth Slows\n\nIf Connectivity segment growth decelerates, several compounding risks emerge:\n\n1. **ARPU Dilution Is Already Eroding Revenue Quality.** Starlink subscriber ARPU declined 11.2% in FY2025 and accelerated to a 22.9% decline in Q1 2026, driven by international expansion into lower-ARPU markets and the introduction of lower-priced service plans. Subscriber growth (104.7% in Q1 2026) must increasingly outrun ARPU headwinds just to sustain revenue momentum. If subscriber growth plateaus while ARPU continues to fall, EBITDA growth could stall.\n\n2. **AI Capex Demands Are Accelerating Beyond Internal Funding Capacity.** At the Q1 2026 annualized run-rate of ~$30.9B, AI capex alone would consume 4.3× the Connectivity segment\'s entire FY2025 EBITDA. Any slowdown in Connectivity cash generation would widen the already-massive funding gap and force greater reliance on external debt and equity markets, which the company accessed for $16,055M in AI-related financing in FY2025 alone.\n\n3. **EchoStar Spectrum Acquisition Adds $19.6B in Capital Commitments.** This pending acquisition, critical for mobile connectivity expansion, represents a substantial additional cash requirement that would compete with AI infrastructure for available internal and external capital.\n\n4. **Competitive and Regulatory Saturation Risks.** Starlink faces competition from terrestrial fiber/5G in dense markets, regulatory and licensing hurdles across international jurisdictions, and dependency on telecom carrier partnerships for satellite-to-mobile services. A slowdown in market penetration would directly compress the EBITDA surplus that cross-subsidizes the broader platform.\n\n5. **Consolidated Free Cash Flow Is Deeply Negative.** With consolidated operating cash flow of $6,785M against $20,737M in capex, the company generated negative free cash flow of approximately $(13,952)M in FY2025. If Connectivity—the sole internal cash engine—falters, the company\'s ability to service its substantial indebtedness and fund its multi-year AI investment horizon would be materially impaired.\n\n6. **AI Segment Has a Multi-Year Path to Positive EBITDA.** Management explicitly warns of a "multi-year investment horizon" before AI investments generate sustained positive Adjusted EBITDA. During this period, Connectivity is effectively the only internal offset to AI cash burn. A Connectivity slowdown would leave external financing as the sole funding source, increasing leverage and refinancing risk.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe Connectivity segment\'s $7,168M Adjusted EBITDA is the platform\'s critical internal cash engine, generating a $2,990M surplus after its own capex. However, this surplus covers only a fraction of the consolidated capital program—particularly as AI capex accelerates toward a ~$31B annualized run-rate. The company\'s investment thesis depends on Connectivity sustaining high growth while AI investments eventually reach scale. If Connectivity growth slows amid ARPU dilution and market saturation, the funding gap would widen materially, forcing increased dependence on capital markets at a time when the company is already taking on substantial debt.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
